Viral infections due to unsafe abortions are major contributors to complications. In Ghana, HIV is the leading cause of maternal mortality, followed by other non-HIV chronic diseases. Substantial investments in public health should be made to promote safe and dignified reproductive health services for all women and girls in Ghana. Providing access to comprehensive holistic care for expectant mothers is crucial in demographic evidence and development as well as sustainability.
Worldwide, arrests of doctors, nurses, and midwives for providing health services, despite clear evidence for greater maternal survival at birth, represents a constant threat to the provision of abortion-related services and puts the health and lives of women at risk (Pitt, et al., 2010). For the untrained provider the complications are high due to ignorant use of crude abortion methods such as ingestion of spices, charcoal, or ingestion of certain local herbs. There are reported deaths resulting from obstetric complications related to unsafe abortions, including hemorrhage, infections, and damage to the reproductive organs as well as long-term health effects such as urinary and fecal incontinence and pelvic organ prolapse (Smith et al., 1996; Singh and Stanton, 2006).
